Aim: Study of Basic commands of Linux. Directory/File:
pwd: Used to display the location of the current working directory. 
mkdir: Used to create a new directory under any directory. 
rmdir: Used to delete a directory. 
ls: Used to display a list of content of a directory. 
touch: Used to create empty files. 
cd: Used to change the current directory. 
cat: Used to create a file, display content, or copy content. 
rm: Used to remove a file. 
tac: Reverse of cat command, displays file content from the last line. 
more: Displays screenful output of a file at a time. 
head: Displays the first 10 lines of a file. 
tail: Displays the last ten lines of a file. 
passwd: Used to create and change the password for a user. 
id: Used to display the user ID (UID) and group ID (GID). 
su: Provides administrative access to another user shell. 
less: Similar to 'more' but includes adjustment in width and height. 
cp: Used to copy a file or directory. 
wc: Returns the number of lines, words, and characters in a file. 
free: Displays RAM details. 
gedit: Used to create and open a file.
